A worker’s representative, Labour Party, explained his group was concerned because “it rhymes with Twp and Pwp.”
For readers outside Wales: In Welsh, twp means «dustete», and pwp means «bush».
A representative of the People's Republic of Wales, Plaid Cymru, said that the group as a whole was 'dissatisfied' and that they have proposed alternatives.
A representative of the Welsh part of the Conservative Party said that his group was 'open' for the name change, but noted that the pronunciation of MWP is very near the word 'Muppet', which, in addition to being the name of some known dolls, is also a British slang word for 'dust'.
In this context, the Welsh letter W is spoken in a similar way to that of the letter U in the Yorkshire dialect, more like an “uh” sound.
The Assembly Commission, which is currently developing laws to introduce the name change, said: \"Of course it is the members themselves who have the final right to determine their names.\"
The Government of Wales Act 2017 authorised the Welsh National Assembly to change its own name.
In June, the Commission published the results of a public consultation which showed general support for the re-juvenating of the Welsh Parliament's National Assembly.
As regards the titles of the representatives, the Commission supported WMPs (Welsh Parlaiment Members), but the MWP option received the most support during the public hearing.
Although the representatives propose other alternatives, to get all parties to reach an agreement may lead to a headbreak for Prime Minister Elin Jones, who will plan to deliver a draft legislation for the name change in the next few weeks.
The legislation on the reform will include other changes in the functioning of the national assembly, including rules on disqualification of representatives and the design of the committee system.
Representatives have the final right to vote on what to call them when discussing the law.
