The whole Indian state of Bolivia has still freshened in memory the coastline they lost to Chile during a bloody resource conflict in the 1800s, and it yearns for once again to sail on the Pacific.
These hopes may be greater than they have been in decades, as Bolivia awaits a ruling from the International Court of Justice on 1 October after five years of discussion.
“Bolivia has a driving force, a Community spirit and peace of mind, and naturally awaits the result with a positive attitude,” said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will see the ruling of the International Court of Justice on a big screen in many different parts of the country, hoping that the Hague Court will give its ruling in favor of Bolivia’s claim that Chile — after decades of sporadic negotiations — is obliged to negotiate to give Bolivia its own exit to the sea.
