John Edward: Language skills are crucial for world citizens
Scotland's free schools are still showing academic excellence, and this has persisted in 2018 with another one year of excellent graduation results. These are supported by individual and common success in sports, art, music and other social measures.
These schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (the Council of Free Schools), have more than 30,000 students throughout Scotland, working hard to deliver the very best school experience to both students and parents.
Free schools aim to prepare their students for further and higher education, their chosen careers, and their position as world citizens.
As an educational body capable of designing and implementing a tailor - made school curriculum, we see modern languages as still a popular and sought - after school election.
Nelson Mandela said: \"If you speak to a man in a language he understands, his words will reach his head.
If you speak to him in his own language, the words will reach his heart.\"
This is a powerful reminder that we cannot stick to English only when we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
From this year's graduation results, we see that languages are at the top of the table with the highest headage rates from free schools.
A total of 68 percent of foreign - language students received the A degree.
The data collected from the 74 member schools of the Finnish Schools showed that 72 percent of students received the A degree in Mandarin, while 72 percent of those studying German, 69 percent of those studying French, and 63 percent of Spanish received A.
This illustrates the fact that high schooling in Scotland supports foreign languages that will undoubtedly be needed in the future as a crucial skill for children and young people.
Language as a specialist choice is now valued at the same level as real science, technology, engineering and mathematics at the curriculum of open schools and elsewhere.
A survey carried out by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills in 2014 revealed that the causes of employers ’ problems with the possession of a vacancy could be attributed to a 17 percent lack of language skills.
Thus, language skills are becoming increasingly important in clarifying young people for a future career.
As more and more job opportunities demand language skills, these skills become crucial in a globalized world.
If you have learned a second language, these lifelong skills will bring real benefits in the future, no matter what career you choose.
Being able to communicate directly with people from other countries will automatically give a multilingual person a competitive advantage.
According to a YouGov survey by more than 4,000 British adults in 2013, 75 percent were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to have a conversation, and French was the only language that was a two-digit number of participants (15 percent) could speak.
This is why investment in language learning is now crucial for today’s children.
Learning more languages, especially those related to emerging economies, will give children better opportunities to find good jobs.
In Scotland, each school teaches different languages.
Many schools will focus on the more classical modern languages, while others will teach the languages that are considered most valuable to Britain on the way to 2020, such as Mandarin and Japanese.
Whatever interests your child, there will always be a choice of languages to choose from in high school, with teachers who are experts in this field.
Scottish Free Schools aim to create a learning environment that will prepare the children and equip them with the knowledge and abilities they need to succeed, no matter what the future holds.
It cannot be denied in today’s global business environment that languages are still crucial for the country’s future, and this must be reflected in teaching.
Modern languages should in fact be considered ‘international communication capacity’.
Free schools will continue to offer this opportunity, diversity and the distinction for Scotland’s young people.
I faut bien le faire.
