Cells can now ‘see’ a protein common in many cancers, then inject into the patient again
A test vaccine has had promising results among patients with different types of cancer.
One woman who received the vaccine, who teaches the immune system to recognise cancer cells, experienced the disappearance of her egg cancer for over 18 months.
The method involves taking immune cells from a patient, changing them in the laboratory so that they can ‘see’ a protein called HER2, which is typical of many cancers, and then inject these cells back into the patient.
Professor Jay Berzofsky of the US National Cancer Institute in Bethesda, Maryland said: “The results indicate that we have a very promising vaccine.”
HER2 ‘reduces the growth of different types of cancer’, including breast cancer, ovarian cancer, lung cancer and colorectal cancer, explained Professor Berzofsky.
A similar procedure, in which immune cells were taken from the patient and trained to address cancer cells, has been effective in treating a type of leukaemia.
