HIV/AIDS: China reports a 14% increase in new cases
China has reported an increase of as much as 14% in the number of people living with HIV and AIDS.
More than 820,000 people are affected in the country, says a health representative.
About 40,000 new cases were reported only in the second quarter of 2018.
The vast majority of new cases are transmitted through sex, which marks a change from the past.
Traditionally, HIV spread rapidly in some parts of China by infection through blood transfusions.
But the number of people who get HIV this way is now closer to zero, said Chinese health care professionals at a conference in Yunnan Province.
Year by year, however, the number of people living with HIV and AIDS in China has increased by 100,000 people.
HIV infection through sex is an acute problem in China's LGBT environment.
Homosexuality was decriminated in China in 1997, but discrimination against LGBT people is said to be high.
Due to the conservative values of the country, studies have estimated that 70-90% of men who have sex with men marry women.
Much of the disease is caused by inadequate sex protection in these conditions.
Since 2003, the Chinese authorities have promised universal access to HIV medicines as part of an action to address the problem.
