National Trust Listens to the Secret Life of the Bats
New research carried out by a rural area in the Highlands of Scotland will reveal how bats use the landscape in the pursuit of food.
There is hope that the findings will shed new light on the behaviour of the unique flying mammals and contribute to the design of future conservation measures.
The study for researchers at the National Trust for Scotland will follow common bats and dwarf bats as well as tanning and water bats at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed at important locations around the property to track bat activity throughout the season.
NHS personnel and volunteers will also conduct mobile investigations using handheld detectors.
Expert sound analyses of all recordings will determine the frequency of the bats and the species that do what.
A habitat map and a report will then be prepared to produce a detailed landscape picture of their behavior.
Rob Dewar, the conservation adviser for the NTS, hopes that the results will reveal which areas of the habitat are most important to the bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will be included in the decision on the measures to be taken, such as the laying of pastures and the best way to protect the forest for bats and other associated species.
The bat population in Scotland and the United Kingdom has fallen considerably over the last century.
They are threatened by construction that affects breeding sites and the reduction of habitats.
Windmills and lighting may also pose a risk, the same as flypapers and certain chemically treated building materials, as well as the attack by house taxes.
In fact, bats are not blind.
But because of their nightly hunting habits, they need ears more than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use advanced echolocation to find insects and obstacles on the road when they fly.
NTS, which is responsible for the maintenance of over 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land around the country, takes bats very seriously.
They have ten skilled experts who regularly carry out research, surveying breeding sites, and sometimes rescue work.
The organisation has also established Scotland's first and only own bat reserve at the Three-country property in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
Property Manager David Thompson says that the property is the ideal territory for them.
\"Here on Three we have a perfect area for bats,\" he says.
“We have the old buildings, a lot of old trees and the ideal habitat.
But there's still a lot we don't know about bats, so the work we do here and other property will help us understand more about what they need to thrive».
He emphasizes the importance of mapping the bats before maintenance is carried out on a property since the accidental destruction of a single breeding site can kill up to 400 females and young people, and perhaps destroy an entire local population.
Bats are protected, and it is illegal to kill them, harass them, or disturb them, or destroy their breeding grounds.
Elisabeth Ferrell, a Scottish member of the Bat Conservation Trust, has encouraged the audience to help in the work.
She says: \"We still have much to learn about our bats, and for many of the species we simply don't know how the populations are doing.\"
