Update on algae flowering: Concentrations are reduced in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report from the Florida Commission on Fisheries and Animal Health (FWC) shows a general decrease in red algae concentrations for parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to FWC, smudged blooms are reported in areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte, and Collier County — indicating reduced concentrations.
A flowering of red algae stretches about 200 miles [210 km] along the coast, from north of Pinellas to south in Lee County.
There are spots around 16 km off the coast of Hillsborough County, but less places than last week.
Red algae have also been observed in Pasco County.
Mean concentrations at or off the coast of Pinellas County last week have been reported to be high off the coast of Hillsborough County, natural to high concentrations in Manatee County, natural to high concentrations at or off the coast of Sarasota County, natural to medium concentrations in Charlotte County, natural to high concentrations at or off the coast of Lee County and low concentrations in Collier County.
There are still reports of irritation in the airways of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee, and Collier County.
There was no reports of irritation in the respiratory tracts northwest of Florida within the last week.
